photos.name: Luminescent
photos.description:
Lake Oberon
Tasmania

I was first drawn to this area by images I saw from a group visiting here in 2015. See Luke Tscharke, Dylan Gehlken, Chris Wiewora and Gavin Owen's images. It certainly didn't disappoint when I finally arrived here last month after a 2016 trip had to be rerouted due to bushfires in the state. I have a series of images from this location and a nearby grove of Pandanis. Working in this area with other photographers can be a challenge not to get in each other's way but I think the 4 of us managed that OK that morning . For reference, a red dot down below can be seen . This was one of our tents pitched on a beach along the lake shore. This is one of very few long exposures that I did for the trip as the drama I felt was much better captured in short exposures. Apologies for the series upcoming - it will literally be this scene with shifting light giving pretty different conditions.
As an aside, this was taken with the new Nisi v5pro holder which I have reservations about - I'll address this in a blog post at a later date.

photos.name: The Colours Of Westminster
photos.description:
London was the place where we went, to talk and drink coffee. Every few weeks, especially in the quiet mornings of winter, you would have found us sat outside a coffee shop, somewhere on the south bank, with out cameras laid out on the table. It was our therapy, our moment. We would walk the relatively quiet streets in search of inspiration and purpose, sometimes we would even find some. Anthony and I were the closest of friends, preferring to spend time with each other than we did any of the handful of other people that were scattered over our lives. We would just up on the coach, or the train, and arrive in London in the early hours. We would then spend the day talking about the big things, and the little things. You can see him here, stood on the bridge, smoking; as he always did.

Those days used to last forever, trapped beneath a blanket of what felt like clean air. Days were longer then, the sun was brighter. The wind was colder and it was always the kind of weather we don't get anymore, weather you can actually feel. 

This is an old photo, from a time when I barely knew which end of the camera to look through. I had already been bitten by the artistic bug, but had yet to discover what art actually was. To me, photography was still about simply recording something, not about changing it into something you wanted it to be. The images are more honest in a way, less contrived.
